Muscle spindle

Source-YouTube <- a good overview


Muscle spindles are organs that sense muscle stretch. They are embedded in muscle, alongside contractile 'extrafusal' muscle fibers.
The 'intrafusal' sensory fibers of the muscle spindle consist of

  • bag fibers and
  • chain fibers
    Innervation:
  • Bag fibers and chain fibers are both innervated by Type 1 neurons -> Group Ia = annulospiral. They are naked neuron endings wrapping around the central parts of the intrafusal fibers.
  • Chain fibers are innervated by Type 2 neurons as well. -> Group II = "flower spray" neurons. They innervate the distal ends of the chain fibers.
  • Motor efferents: find gamma fibers innervate the contractile areas of the intrafusal fibers described below.

The afferents (Group Ia and Group II) have slow adapting and fast adapting fibers which sense absolute length and rate of change of length, respectively.

The ends of the chain fibers contain contractile areas which 'take up the slack' when the muscle contracts, to keep the chain fiber taught.

The lengthening and shortening of muscles is detected by the muscle spindles.
The tension of the muscle is detected by the tendon spindles. (Golgi tendon organ)


Viral influenza

Why is vaccination so common?

  • Because influenza is very common, highly contagious and can cause symptoms from mild febrile illness to respiratory failure and death.
  • 5000 to 14000 estimated deaths in the 2021-22 season.
  • The commonest complication is influenza pneumonia.

People with high risk of complications

  • Age > 65 or < 5;
  • almost any medical cormorbidity
  • Pregnant or 2 weeks post partum

Tranmission - very high risk because:

  • Incubation period - 2 days; but transmission can occur before symptoms onset and even from asymptomatic persons.
  • For influenza, close contact included speaking face-to-face;

Diagnosis: Usually clinical but if necessary, viral culture from nasopharyngeal swabs is the gold standard. Antigen kits are specific but not very sensitive.

Management:

  • Mainstay is prevention with the vaccine; new vaccines are now quadrivalent. (2 A subtypes and 2 B subtypes)
  • In the norther hemisphere, all persons over 6 months of age should receive the vaccine.
  • Vaccines should be given regardless of ALLERGY history if means to treat anaphylaxis are available.Source
  • Some vaccines use egg based cultures.
  • Vaccination is recommended for any trimester of pregnancy. It also confirms protection to the newborn.

Drugs:

  • Oseltamivir is a neuraminidase inhibitor.
  • Neuraminidase inhibitors interfere with release of progeny influenza virus from infected cells.
    • Oseltamivir reduces duration of symptoms and duration of viral shedding.
    • Treatment duration is 5 days.
  • Oseltamivir and others are approved for treatment and prophylaxis.
  • Vaccines are the best method of prevention. However, if vaccine is contraindicated or ineffective (patient is immunosuppresed), antivirals (oseltamivir) can be used for prophylaxis.
  • #pregnancy is NOT a contraindication for oseltamivir.
  • Alternative regimens: IV peramivir, inhaled zanamavir (but it can cause bronchoconstrition; CI in asthma)
  • Other drugs include Amantadine (yet.. antiparkinsons drug) and rimantadine which blocks the viral M2 proton channel but there is not high resistance to these drugs (in the USA) so not recommended for use there.

[!INFO] H5N1 - is avian influenza.

Symptoms:

  • Uncomplicated disease
    • Fever, corrhyzal symptoms
    • Constitutional symptoms
    • Red and watery eyes
    • Non productive Cough
    • Sore throat
  • Older adults and immunosuppresed patients may have fewer symptoms but confusion is commoner among older patients.
  • Physical examination of the lungs is normal
  • Complicated disease
    • Pneumonia - usually occurs within a few days of onset: cough becomes purulent and productive. Commonest cause is Strep. pneumoniae. Source
    • Myocarditis, pericarditis, myocardial infarction, CNS involvement, myositis, rhabdomyolysis can all occur.
    • CNS: Seizures, encephalitis, Guillain barre syndrome,
    • It can also cause a parkinson like syndrome called "encephalitis lethargica" Source

Grades of COPD

[!INFO] Grades of airflow limitation

This is GOLD 1,2,3,4 <- a grading of severity; used ?mostly at diagnosis.

GOLD A,B,C,D are different gradings which classify symptoms burden and risk of exacerbation-see below. These classifications are the ones used to guide therapy.
so 80, 50, and 30% (not the prerequisite for FEV1/FVC < 0.7)

[!INFO] Grades for initiation treatment

COPS management steps flow from left to right of this image; the final grid is used to classify the severity in order to determine the level of treatment required.

Non pharmacologic measures

  • Smoking cessation; counseling even for short periods by HCPs is beneficial.

    • Nicotine replacement therapy (gum, patches etc) can be used.
    • e-cigarrettes have not been proven to be safe.

  • Vaccinations:

    • Influenza vaccine, pneumococcal vaccine and since 2021, Tdap (pertussis) vaccine and zoster vaccine (for people aged > 50) are recommended.

  • Pharmacological therapy:

    • All patients with COPD should be prescribed a rescue short-acting bronchodilator for immediate symptom relief.
    • Group A - initiate SABA or LABA
    • Group B - initiate LABA or LAMA (tiotropium, glycopryrolate, aclidinium, umeclidinium)
      • Either one is equally effective; choice is patient specific.
    • Group C - LAMA; LAMA is superior to LABA in preventing exacerbations.
      • (studies have showed that tiotropium is more effective than LABA)
    • Group D - LAMA or LAMA + LABA
      • If history suggestive of asthma or eosinophils > 300 / microLiter ->
        ICS + LABA
    • Role of inhaled corticosteroids:
      • #2019GM-OCT/Q09
      • ICS alone has no benefit.
      • ICS with LABA does have benefit (in fact, they show synergistic effect) in moderate to severe COPD.
    • Azithromycin can be given for former smokers with frequent exacerbations.

Alpha glucosidase inhibitors

They prevent the digestion and absorption of complex carbohydrates.
Prevents the last step of digestion: ie. prevents disaccharide -> monosaccharide conversion and thus slows absorption.
Efficacy: 'limited efficacy' according to K&C.
GI side effects are common.
Therefore, not widely used.

Colesevelam

A bile acid sequestrant that can also lower blood glucose; mechanism is unknown.

[!INFO] Remember: The obliques Abduct!
"oh bee" -> "eh bee"

The axis of the eye is not aligned with the axis of the extraocular muscles. Source-YouTube
Therefore, elevation and depression are not controlled solely by the superior and inferior rectus. There is contribution from the obliques as well.
To isolate the recti, the axis of the eye should be rotated away from the line of action of the obliques.
(i.e the action of the obliques is minimized when the eye is abducted)

Therefore, to test the eye muscles, the eye movements must be carried out as follows:

Diagnosis only requires the presence of non-reversible airflow obstruction as evidenced by 📑FEV1/FVC < 0.7 (in the appropriate clinical context).
(i.e FEV1 is low compared to FVC)
